observation data analysis

which is I believe exibition data assuming ekspot is exibition windows and czas_w_sek is average time taken by student at each window.

exhibitAnalysis = observation_data %>% group_by(ekspot) %>% summarise(avg_time_to_view = mean(czas_w_sek), id_counts = n_distinct(ID))
#here we see how many students stayed on each exibition window on an average time.

summary(exhibitAnalysis$avg_time_to_view)

#Students Analysis
#Here we will find out which students visited most windows and his view window time.

studentAnalysis = observation_data %>% group_by(ID) %>% summarise(avg_time_to_view = mean(czas_w_sek), expotCount = n_distinct(ekspot))
studentAnalysis$ID <- factor(studentAnalysis$ID)

ordered <- studentAnalysis[with(studentAnalysis, order(-avg_time_to_view)), ][0:10,]
## here we have a list of students who took a lot of time at some of the windows, which are very interesting to them...analysing them... keen to learn and understand student..or they spent a lot of time observing tings( interesting-strange or new )

ordered <- studentAnalysis[with(studentAnalysis, order(-expotCount)), ][0:10,]
## here we see the ids of students who visted maximum spots in less time...running here and there..and finish

Reading descriptions

We will analyse the variable Opis(read description of spot/window) which is a flag and define relationship between reading description and grades

reading_time_grade_relation = data %>% group_by(opis) %>% summarise(avg_time_to_view = mean(czas_w_sek), avg_ocem = mean(na.omit(oceM)), avg_ocejp = mean(na.omit(oceJP)), avg_ocep = mean(na.omit(oceP)), id_counts = n_distinct(ID))
reading_time_grade_relation 
## # A tibble: 2 × 6
##    opis avg_time_to_view avg_ocem avg_ocejp avg_ocep id_counts
##   <int>            <dbl>    <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>     <int>
## 1     1         66.97272 3.754325  3.916373 3.867021       108
## 2    NA         65.92228 3.504264  3.806505 3.811281       132
## here we see that there is very slight difference between grades of students who read and whose who dont read description...may be because some students understand things by reading whereas others by observing in detail...

zach attribute analysis:

4 types of zach are :1 - patrzenie; 2 - dotykanie, 3 - uzywanie, 4 - eksperymentowanie

summary(observation_data$zach)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##   1.000   2.000   3.000   2.432   3.000   4.000     887
zach_analysis = observation_data %>% group_by(zach) %>% summarise(avg_time_to_view = mean(czas_w_sek), id_counts = n_distinct(ID),  expotCount = n_distinct(ID))
zach_analysis <- zach_analysis[complete.cases(zach_analysis[, 'zach']),]

zach_analysis$zach <- as.character(zach_analysis$zach)
zach_analysis$zach[zach_analysis$zach == '1'] <- "patrzenie"
zach_analysis$zach[zach_analysis$zach == '2'] <- "dotykanie"
zach_analysis$zach[zach_analysis$zach == '3'] <- "uzywanie"
zach_analysis$zach[zach_analysis$zach == '4'] <- "eksperymentowanie"

summary(zach_analysis$avg_time_to_view)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   34.12   36.16   49.16   58.96   71.96  103.40
boxplot(zach_analysis$avg_time_to_view, horizontal = TRUE, main="Average time Duration")

summary(zach_analysis$id_counts)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   110.0   125.0   130.5   125.8   131.2   132.0
boxplot(zach_analysis$id_counts, horizontal = TRUE, main="Student Count")

summary(zach_analysis$expotCount)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   110.0   125.0   130.5   125.8   131.2   132.0
boxplot(zach_analysis$expotCount, horizontal = TRUE, main="Unit Count")

ggplot(zach_analysis, aes(x="", y=avg_time_to_view, fill=zach)) +
geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity")+ coord_polar("y", start=0) + 
  theme_void() +
    ggtitle("Average time spent")

ggplot(zach_analysis, aes(x="", y=id_counts, fill=zach)) +
geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity")+ coord_polar("y", start=0) + 
  theme_void() +
    ggtitle("Students Count")

ggplot(zach_analysis, aes(x="", y=expotCount, fill=zach)) +
geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity")+ coord_polar("y", start=0) + 
  theme_void() +
    ggtitle("unit Count")

Parents Analysis :

how grades are related to parent’s work status ( currently working or not)

Parentanalysis for mother

workingMom = data %>% group_by(pracaM) %>% summarise(avg_time_to_view = mean(czas_w_sek), subject_1 = mean(na.omit(oceM)), subject_2 = mean(na.omit(oceJP)), subject_3 = mean(na.omit(oceP)))

workingMom <- workingMom[complete.cases(workingMom[, 'pracaM']),]

workingMom$pracaM <- as.character(workingMom$pracaM)
workingMom$pracaM[workingMom$pracaM == '1'] <- "Yes"
workingMom$pracaM[workingMom$pracaM == '2'] <- "No"
workingMom$pracaM[workingMom$pracaM == '3'] <- "I do not know"

ggplot(data=workingMom, aes(x=pracaM, y=avg_time_to_view)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="pink") +
    ggtitle("Mom's work status by Average Duration")  +
    xlab("Mom's work status") +
    ylab("Average Duration [s]")

ggplot(data=workingMom, aes(x=pracaM, y=subject_1)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="pink") +
    ggtitle("Mom's work status by subject_1 Grade")  +
    xlab("mom's work status") +
    ylab("Average subject_1  Grade]")

ggplot(data=workingMom, aes(x=pracaM, y=subject_2)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="pink") +
    ggtitle("mom's work status by Average subject_2 Grade")  +
    xlab("mom's work status") +
    ylab("Average subject_2  Grade")

ggplot(data=workingMom, aes(x=pracaM, y=subject_3)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="pink") +
    ggtitle("mom's work status by subject_3 Grade")  +
    xlab("mom's work status") +
    ylab("Average subject_3  Grade")

so here we see that students with working mom are better performing(grades and longer view time) then the student who dont even know about there mom’s working status.conclusion is that working mom’s have better performing kids.

Parentanalysis for Dad

workingDad = data %>% group_by(pracaT) %>% summarise(avg_time_to_view = mean(czas_w_sek), subject_1 = mean(na.omit(oceM)), subject_2 = mean(na.omit(oceJP)), subject_3 = mean(na.omit(oceP)))
workingDad <- workingDad[complete.cases(workingDad[, 'pracaT']),]

workingDad$pracaT <- as.character(workingDad$pracaT)
workingDad$pracaT[workingDad$pracaT == '1'] <- "Yes"
workingDad$pracaT[workingDad$pracaT == '2'] <- "No"
workingDad$pracaT[workingDad$pracaT == '3'] <- "I do not know"

ggplot(data=workingDad, aes(x=pracaT, y=avg_time_to_view)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="light blue") +
    ggtitle("Dad's work status by Average Duration")  +
    xlab("Dad's work status") +
    ylab("Average Duration [s]")

## here we see that Dad working status doesnot influence kids behaviour

ggplot(data=workingDad, aes(x=pracaT, y=subject_1)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="light blue") +
    ggtitle("Dad's work status by Average subject_1 Grade")  +
    xlab("Dad's work status") +
    ylab("Average subject_1 Grade]")

## students who dont know there dad's working status are bad performing in subject 1

ggplot(data=workingDad, aes(x=pracaT, y=subject_3)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="light blue") +
    ggtitle("Dad's work status by Average subject_2 Grade")  +
    xlab("Dad's work status") +
    ylab("Average subject_2 Grade")

## students who know that there dad is working are performing good in subject 2

ggplot(data=workingDad, aes(x=pracaT, y=subject_3)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="light blue") +
    ggtitle("Dad's work status by Average subject_3 Grade")  +
    xlab("Dad's work status") +
    ylab("Average subject_3 Grade")

## students who know that there dad is working are performing good in subject 3
## so we conclude that students with working dad are better performing

Conclusions Even though the correlation matrix did not show any correclation between different attributes, but from above we can see correlation between student’s grades and parents working status, and time they spend on exploring exhibitionshas impact on there grades… so correlation existed but not higher then 60%
